informal_proof:
The inverse of $5\pmod{7}$ is 3, since $5\cdot3 \equiv 1\pmod{7}$. Also, inverse of $2\pmod{7}$ is 4, since $2\cdot 4\equiv 1\pmod{7}$. Finally, the inverse of $3\pmod{7}$ is 5 (again because $5\cdot3 \equiv 1\pmod{7}$). So the residue of $2^{-1}+3^{-1}$ is the residue of $4+5\pmod{7}$, which is $2$. Thus $L-R=3-2=1$. Since the left-hand side $L$ and the right-hand side $R$ of the equation $$
(a+b)^{-1} \stackrel{?}{=} a^{-1} + b^{-1} \pmod{m}
$$are not equal, we may conclude that the equation is not true in general.
